<br>
What struck me most about this episode was the contrast between John as sullen, bitter legal clerk/angry punk at the  beginning, and John as broken-hearted but humane lover at the end.  The catalyst, of course, being Unagor's partially-successful attempt to possess John and force him to carry out his darkest fantasies.  Once again in this series, however, humanity gains victory over demonkind.  Well, a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>moral</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> victory, anyway, considering John's and Puce's fate.<br>
<br>
I also loved the Genital Warts' lyrics and the goth audience's response.  (Can't help but wonder what Caitlin R. Kiernan would have done with that scene...probably she would have had Echo and Gabriel come and kill the band <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )  And then of course there was poor Mrs. Silverman's pathetic attempt to warn John--in Yiddish!--that there was a devil in his apartment.  (BTW, Mike, a minor correction:  the correct way to say &quot;Woe is me!&quot;  is,  &quot;Vey iz mir!&quot;  The word &quot;gevalt&quot; does mean &quot;woe,&quot; but only as an interjection.)<br>
<br>
Finally, I'd like to put in a vote for Ken Lopez replacing Comicraft (whoever that is) as letterer, on an ongoing basis.  The letterer's art is an overlooked but essential one, and I just don't think that computerized fonts do justice to a comic of this literary and artistic caliber.  Thank you and good night. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(12/19/03 8:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #45 Discussion Thread (Spoilers)</span><hr size=1> Intriguing observation about the Hempel/McKean cross-talk Ashmodai.  I can't recall the name of the artist I was thinking of when I did my first quick-read earlier tonight, but Gaydos's name keeps blinking on my brain.  That may have something to do with his new book that's also just out this week.<br>
<br>
Remind me to consult you when I'm to this issue in the second volume of annotations.  My background in Yiddish is negative zero.<br>
<br>
Here here on Ken Lopez's unbelievable fontwork.  Comicraft's done a fine job, but Mr. Lopez is simply without peer.  Until someone digitizes his style, that is.  :P<br>
<br>
This is another fantastic example of a good place for new readers to come onboard the series, so if any of you out there browsing by (and I know you're there, with the 100+ guest hits I'm seeing each day <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    ) pick up <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Lucifer #45</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then come on back here and visit <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lightbringer.mattpeckham.com/lucifer/story_so_far.htm" target="top">The Story So Far</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->... to play catch up, then if you're still with us, grab the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://lightbringer.mattpeckham.com/lucifer/collections.htm" target="top">trades</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (#5 hits in just a few weeks) and welcome yourself to the club.<br>
<br>
p.s. Mike sends word from the Plane of Writeaholicism: he'll be back to grace our ranks soon, and thanks to his recent writerly tribulations, there's going to be plenty more of Mike to go around in the coming months and years. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mcpeckham>mcpeckham</A> at: 12/19/03 9:02 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wulfenbach>wulfenbach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(12/22/03 5:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #45 Discussion Thread (Spoilers)</span><hr size=1> The Yiddish meant something relevant?  Cool.<br>
<br>
The goth/punk thing passed over me.  Those lyrics were recognizably punk?  Which wouldn't go over well in a goth club?<br>
<br>
So when did Lucifer become the defender of Order?  When that became necessary to defend existence, I guess.  I was wondering last issue about &quot;convergence or chiasm&quot;, implying that both Lucifer and Michael are moving.  Michael's prideful and sullen, but what are Lucifer's changes?  He's yet to become more obviously compassionate as a result of his near-death experiences (the way Dream changed.)  It's ironic that he ended up defending Heaven, with the angels almost ready to rally behind him -- right now I think &quot;son of God&quot; trumps &quot;rebel&quot; in their leaderless confusion -- but under the circumstances it seemed in character. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ian@lucifer>ian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(12/23/03 12:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Lucifer #45 Discussion Thread</span><hr size=1> This issue made me realise that Lucifer really is his father's son. He seems to have no problem telling people (or demons) how things are going to be, and if they dont like it, then tough shit. I don't know why I didnt realise that before, what with Lucifer's fairly rigid rules about worship in his cosmos. He claims to be all for free will, but at the same time effectively outlaws religion in his own universe. How is this any different than the way Yahweh rules his universe? Its pretty much the extreme opposite, and therefore almost the same. Just one of the many things I love about this comic. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=backwards7>backwards7</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(1/1/04 7:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   let it bleed</span><hr size=1> One of my new year's resolutions is to try and participate more in the online discussions of the various titles that I read. This is a Lucifer forum so I guess occasionally it would be good form to write about Lucifer.<br>
<br>
I read Lucifer #45 on the late train to Southend from London Liverpool Street Station. This train is known as 'The Vomit Comet' presumably because you have to wait what seems like a century for it to arrive and, when it does finally pull into the station, it quickly fills up with drunk office workers.<br>
<br>
I was drunk too and, in my addled mind, the demon - Unagor - had a head that looked like the cake on the front cover of The Rolling Stones album - Let It Bleed.<br>
<br>
I think the issues of Lucifer that I've enjoyed the most are the ones where you see how Lucifer's plans, and also the plots of his enemies, occasionally impact on an unsuspecting individual. It's always someone random, just going about their day to day business. This is a theme that runs through the title and it's one of the things that makes it for me.<br>
<br>
The attitude of these demons never seems to be particularly malicious because that would imply that these human beings had some kind of significance as opposed to being a race that generally minds it's own business and stays out of the affairs of gods and devils. <br>
<br>
These demons treat people in the same callous manner that a bored kid with a magnifying glass might treat a nest of ants.<br>
<br>
I like the way Lucifer turns up at the end of the issue and it's like he was just passing through on his way to dealing with something more important.  From his point of view, shutting down these rogue demons is a minor detail to be taken care of quickly, like remembering to post a letter on the way to work. It's ironic because just as the hopes and dreams of John Baxter Sewell seem insignificant and amusing to Unagor, in turn Unagor's plans are ridiculous and pointless to Lucifer.<br>
<br>
This issue reminded me a bit of a movie I saw a few years ago where this demon called 'Azzazel' (know I've probably spelt that wrong) takes possession of people's bodies and turns them into temporary serial killers before moving on. It wasn't a bad movie but John Goodman sings in it which always earns a film a couple of black marks in my book. I wish that I could remember what it was called. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=backwards7>backwards7</A> at: 1/1/04 7:14 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eirikraude>Eirik Raude</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(1/4/04 7:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Powergames</span><hr size=1> The movie, Backwards7, was called &quot;Fallen&quot;, and featured Denzel Washington, who did a good job, as usual.<br>
<br>
Anyway, I agree that the episodes where normal people's lives collide with Lucifer (&amp; others') are highly enjoyable. The whole &quot;Children and monsters&quot; arc had that quality, with poor mr. Easterman as the puppet on a string.<br>
<br>
The thing that makes these so enjoyable is that you get to see just what kind of scale is involved in the powergames L &amp; the rest play. The comparison with a kid with a magnifying glass is an apt one.<br>
<br>
And Ian: You're absolutely right, in my opinion. We discussed this a while ago, and one of the points that came up is that Lucifer isn't really interested in free will as a principle, but free will for himself. And if he's to have absolutely free will, then everyone else's will have to be curtailed to a certain degree. That's why Death was so right when she claimed that Lucifer and Yahweh are very similar, something that rankled Lucifer a lot... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> offhandz</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF99>(1/6/04 12:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   three thumbs up</span><hr size=1> great to read the comments in this thread....<br>
<br>
Some of my favorite issues (#4 and 24. oh, let's also add 33 and Nirvana while we're at it) have Lucifer making a late entrance. Though this issue doesn't have Gaudium, Elaine, et al - it was an awfully good story. <br>
<br>
